snippet: If a primary candidate ever deserved the distinction of “inevitable,” it is Hillary Clinton today. Yet nothing would be inevitable in the general election.
abstract: The Upshot; strength with which Hillary Rodham Clinton enters Democratic race for 2016 presidential nomination is unprecedented, and she can reasonably be characterized as being inevitable nominee; absence of viable rivals suggests that path to nomination may be easy, but it by no means is indication that general election will be.
lead_paragraph: If a primary candidate ever deserved the distinction of “inevitable,” it is Hillary Clinton today. Yet nothing would be inevitable in the general election.

headline.main: Huge Head Start for Hillary Clinton, but the Big Race Is Far From Won
headline.print_headline: A Big Early Lead, but No Sure Thing for the General Election
